<h2>Oakland Energy Incentives</h2>
<p>Oakland residents have access to substantial solar and HVAC incentives that significantly reduce installation costs. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the entire system cost, including installation, and can be carried forward if it exceeds annual tax liability.</p>

<p>California offers additional incentives through the Self-Generation Incentive Program (SGIP) for battery storage systems, providing rebates of \$200-\$400 per kWh of storage capacity. PG&E customers can benefit from net energy metering (NEM 3.0), though recent changes emphasize the importance of battery storage for maximizing solar returns. The Bay Area Air Quality Management District offers rebates up to \$3,000 for high-efficiency heat pumps, while the California Energy Commission's TECH Clean California program provides additional heat pump incentives. Oakland also participates in Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing, allowing homeowners to finance solar and HVAC improvements through their property taxes with no upfront costs.</p>

